:"contributions","id":"34936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42349"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91450"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent for routine childhood vaccinations. She appears well with vital signs within normal limits. On examination, a raised, red, well-circumscribed lesion is noted on her abdomen (Image). Her parent reports that this \u0027birthmark\u0027 has been present since shortly after birth. There are no other similar lesions elsewhere on her body. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Campbell de Morgan spot","Infantile haemangioma","Petechiae","Amelanotic melanoma","Keloid scar"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image and clinical description are consistent with an \u003Cstrong\u003Einfantile haemangioma\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as a strawberry naevus. These benign vascular tumours typically appear around the second week of life and grow rapidly during the first few months. The majority spontaneously resolve by the age of nine years. The child\u0027s parents should be reassured that no treatment is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECampbell de Morgan spot\u003C/strong\u003E, or cherry angioma, is a type of capillary haemangioma that is a relatively common incidental finding in older adults. About 75% of individuals over the age of 75 years have these angiomas. They are not typically present in young children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPetechiae\u003C/strong\u003E are small, round, non-blanching spots that appear on the skin due to bleeding under the skin\u0027s surface. They are not raised or palpable and would not persist for years as described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eamelanotic melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare form of skin cancer that lacks pigmentation. While it could potentially have a similar appearance to the lesion described, it is extremely uncommon in children and would not have been present since birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeloid scar\u003C/strong\u003E is an overgrowth of scar tissue that can occur after skin trauma or surgery. While it can have a vascular component, the entire scar would not appear as uniformly vascular as the lesion in the image. Additionally, keloids are not typically present from birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplications of infantile haemangiomas can include ulceration and functional impairment when the haemangioma is large (e.g., obstruction of vision if near the eye, or feeding difficulties if near the mouth). In rare cases, they can be associated with more serious conditions, such as laryngeal haemangioma when there is involvement of the oral cavity, or posterior fossa malformations with large hemifacial haemangiomas. For larger persistent lesions, beta-blockers such as propranolol may be used as treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most infantile haemangiomas will spontaneously resolve by the age of nine years.","Infantile haemangiomas typically appear around the second week of life and are generally benign.","Propranolol may be used to treat larger persistent infantile haemangiomas."],"references":["Smith CJF, Friedlander SF, Guma M, et al. Infantile Hemangiomas: An Updated Review on Risk Factors, Pathogenesis, and Treatment. Birth Defects Res 2017;109809-15. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28402073/","Surlis T, De aSa Reilly H, Sadlier M, et al. Infantile haemangiomas. BMJ 2022;378:e068734. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35793832/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75121"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1594"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15972"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15972"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5cf37c8e-c683-4ce3-9daa-93941ab3a2f2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5cf37c8e-c683-4ce3-9daa-93941ab3a2f2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":598}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75121"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-15T20:13:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-13T14:02:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1594"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91450"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","l